## Quiz

?? If we doubled the resistance $R$ (keeping $C$ the same), what happens to the shape of the $V_C(t)$ curve?
>> The time constant $\tau = RC$ doubles. The curve has the same shape but stretches horizontally — the capacitor now takes twice as long to reach any given fraction of $V_0$. The final voltage is unchanged.

?? At $t = \tau$ the capacitor holds 63% of $V_0$. What fraction of the total energy stored at "full charge" does it hold at that moment?
>> Energy stored in a capacitor is $\tfrac{1}{2}CV^2$, so at $V_C = 0.63 V_0$ the stored energy is $(0.63)^2 \approx 40\%$ of the final energy. The voltage is 63% but the energy lags — you need $t \approx 2.7\tau$ to reach half the total stored energy.
